{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513376"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:08:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:08:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12103"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12103"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.05,0.6,0.11,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4648"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78427"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4648"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12103"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63789"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"124"},{"type":"tags","id":"286"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1216"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7073"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7097"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44823"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78427"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with intermittent pain and discolouration of her fingers (Image 1). These symptoms are often brought on by cold and persist despite attempts to warm them. This has been occurring once or twice a week during the winter months and is causing quite a bit of distress. She also complains of tightening on the skin of the hands, mild joint pain and difficulty swallowing food. On examination of her upper limbs, the skin changes are limited to the hands, not extending beyond the boundary of the wrists. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antibodies is the most likely to return a positive result?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-Ro antibodies","Anti-cardiolipin antibodies","Anti-centromere antibodies","Anti-dsDNA antibodies","Anti-CCP"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EScleroderma is a chronic autoimmune condition that can be divided into different classifications depending upon the symptoms present in the patient. Scleroderma is very heterogeneous in its presentation, hence specific subset classifications of the condition are used to aid clinicians in determining the likely presentations / symptoms to be aware of, aids in prognostication of the condition and indicates the more likely complications to arise for the given patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient is suffering from limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis, which is characterised by symptoms such as joint pain, calcinosis nodules under the skin, Raynaud\u0027s phenomena, oesophageal dysmotility, skin thickening usually limited to the hands and telangiectasia. In this case, the Raynaud\u0027s may be differentiable from physiological Raynaud\u0027s by the patient\u0027s inability to return the digits to normal colour despite attempts to warm them. Similarly, this presentation may be differentiated from diffuse cutaneous systemic sclerosis by the limitation of the skin thickening to the hands. If it were to extend more proximally than the boundaries of the elbows, to the trunk or beyond the knees, the diagnosis would be more difficult to differentiate between these two subsets.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntibodies specific for this form of scleroderma (limited) are \u003Cstrong\u003Eanti-centromere antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E. Anti-centromere antibodies are present in ~40-50% of patient with limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis. They are less commonly found in diffuse cutaneous systemic sclerosis which is more typically associated with anti-RNA polymerase III or anti-topoisomerase I (also called anti-Scl70) autoantibodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-cardiolipin antibodies \u003C/strong\u003Eare often used to assess a patient for their likelihood of anti-phospholipid syndrome, a manifestation often attributed or occurring alongside SLE. Whilst patients with scleroderma may also demonstrate positive results for anti-cardiolipin antibodies, this is not the most specific to this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-Ro antibodies \u003C/strong\u003Eare more indicative of Sjogren\u0027s disease, however there is some overlap of syndromes in terms of their serum antibodies. These antibodies may also be seen in systemic lupus erythematosus, systemic sclerosis and myositis, however is not the best answer here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-dsDNA antibodies \u003C/strong\u003Eare very specific for SLE, hence is not the correct option in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-CCP \u003C/strong\u003Eis used in the investigation of rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["There are classifications of scleroderma that aid clinicians in determining likely features and antibody investigations in these patients.","Limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis is associated with anti-centromere antibodies, while diffuse cutaneous systemic sclerosis is more commonly associated with anti-Scl70 antibodies."],"references":["Nihtyanova SI, Denton CP. Autoantibodies as predictive tools in systemic sclerosis. Nat Rev Rheumatol. 2010 Feb;6(2):112-6. doi: 10.1038/nrrheum.2009.238. PMID: 20125179. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20125179/","van Leeuwen NM, Boonstra M, Bakker JA, Grummels A, Jordan S, Liem S, Distler O, Hoffmann-Vold AM, Melsens K, Smith V, Truchetet ME, Scherer HU, Toes R, Huizinga TWJ, de Vries-Bouwstra JK. Anticentromere Antibody Levels and Isotypes and the Development of Systemic Sclerosis. Arthritis Rheumatol. 2021 Dec;73(12):2338-2347. doi: 10.1002/art.41814. Epub 2021 Nov 2. PMID: 34042326; PMCID: PMC9297867. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34042326/","Nihtyanova SI, Denton CP. Autoantibodies as predictive tools in systemic sclerosis. Nat Rev Rheumatol. 2010 Feb;6(2):112-6. doi: 10.1038/nrrheum.2009.238. PMID: 20125179. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20125179/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63789"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12103"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17479"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17479"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5de15f57-350e-45f9-8dc2-7c1bdf0fd2f9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5de15f57-350e-45f9-8dc2-7c1bdf0fd2f9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":421}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63789"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T18:30:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T18:31:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4648"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78427"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":n